title: SpaceX launches U.S. Space Force’s first mission of 2023 on Falcon Heavy
summary: A SpaceX Falcon Heavy lifted off Jan. 15 at 5:56 p.m. Eastern from Launch Complex 39A at Kennedy Space Center, Florida, carrying the U.S. Space Force USSF-67 mission to geostationary Earth orbit.

title: Watch live: SpaceX set to launch first of five Falcon Heavy missions this year
summary: A trickle of Falcon Heavy launches may soon turn into a flood.

title: SpaceX Falcon Heavy rocket kicks off fifth mission with most spectacular launch yet
summary: SpaceX’s fifth Falcon Heavy lifted off shortly after sunset on the US Space Force’s USSF-67 mission, producing one of the massive commercial...

title: United States and Japan sign space cooperation framework agreement
summary: The United States and Japan signed an agreement Jan. 13 to enable further cooperation between the two countries in space exploration, but without announcing any new initiatives.

title: NASA studying thruster problem with lunar cubesat
summary: Engineers are troubleshooting thruster problems on a cubesat launched last month to search for water ice at the moon, the latest in a series of technical issues among small satellites recently launched to the moon and beyond.

title: SpaceX Falcon Heavy launches USSF-67 from 39A
summary: The latest Falcon Heavy mission launched Sunday, Jan. 15, at 5:56 PM EST (22:56 UTC).

title: US, Japan Sign Space Collaboration Agreement at NASA Headquarters
summary: During an event hosted by NASA Administrator Bill Nelson and Deputy Administrator Pam Melroy at the agency’s Headquarters in Washington Friday, representatives from the United States and Japan gathered to sign an agreement that builds on a long history of collaboration in space exploration between the two nations.

title: Dragonfly mission heads toward PDR, element fabrication from Lockheed Martin set to begin
summary: Dragonfly, NASA’s unique robotic exploration mission using a rotorcraft to fly a science laboratory around the surface of Saturn’s moon Titan, is continuing to march through its preliminary design steps.

title: NorthStar using Axelspace’s Earth-imaging satellites to monitor orbits
summary: Five Earth observation satellites from Japan’s Axelspace are helping NorthStar Earth and Space keep tabs on orbits ahead of the Canadian firm’s proposed Space Situational Awareness constellation.

title: Space Force weighing new approach for selecting national security launch providers
summary: An option under consideration for NSSL Phase 3 is to create “on ramps” to allow emerging launch providers to compete
